About this hotel

In the old medina, this palatial riad in a Hispano-Moorish property is a 10-minute walk from the bustling Jama El f’na, and 2 km from Majorelle Garden and Berber Museum.

Check-in time: 2:00 PM
Check-out time: 12:00 PM

    A wonderful traditional house (small palace) turned into restaurant and guest house in the Medina, the ancient parts of Marrackech.     Sally Leung2 years ago on Google
    5/5
    Location! Location! Location! This hotel is in an amazing location. I actually learned that this hotel used to be part of the Royal palace, which is literally right next door. Apparently, the King doesn't really use that palace as much …
    Location! Location! Location! This hotel is in an amazing location. I actually learned that this hotel used to be part of the Royal palace, which is literally right next door. Apparently, the King doesn't really use that palace as much anymore, but cool nonetheless. With that being said, there are always guards nearby which gave it a sense of more security honestly especially when we were walking by at night.
    My friend and I got to Marrakech in the later afternoon, so we didn't have too much time for sightseeing, but was able to get to Dar El Bacha Museum of the Confluences since it was about a 2 minute walk from the hotel. In addition, this is in walking location to a ton of good restaurants including Nomad, Le Jardin, Dar Moha, etc.
    Our room was (Koutubia) was also HUGE for two people, so I would have to imagine the other rooms might be pretty spacious. I thought their breakfast was also pretty good and had a good variety compared to the 4 other hotels I stayed at during my Moroccan vacation.
    I would definitely recommend this place and would stay here again if I am back in Marrakech!

The Riad is of high level with gorgeous Arabic decorations and a magnificent swimming pool lit up in a beautiful emerald green colour at night. It is possible to negotiate a discount according to the length of the stay. The members of the staff are extremely helpful and polite, I highly recommend it for a full immersion in real Moroccan tradition with glamour.

    Mouassine

    Lively Mouassine is known for traditional markets like the dyers’ souk, with expanses of colorful hanging yarn, and the metalwork souk, where artisans hammer copper. Small shops selling kaftans and lamps sit beside chic decor boutiques, cool cafes and hip Moroccan fusion restaurants. Musée de Mouassine is a restored 16th-century riad with painted woodwork, while Le Jardin Secret has pavilions, gardens and a cafe.

    About this hotel

    In the old medina, this palatial riad in a Hispano-Moorish property is a 10-minute walk from the bustling Jama El f’na, and 2 km from Majorelle Garden and Berber Museum. …

    The 5 individually decorated, elegant suites have Wi-Fi, flat-screen TVs, safes and minibars. All feature lounges and exquisite furnishings. Some add terraces and/or marble bathrooms, and 1 offers a stained-glass dome.

    Breakfast is available. Other amenities include a refined restaurant, and an ornate bar with a fireplace and a patio. There's also an outdoor pool surrounded by courtyard gardens and terrace seating.
